<p>Who are you?</p>

<p>Don&#8217;t be afraid by the simplicity of the question. Some people scoff at it because they think it&#8217;s too easy to answer. Really, when you can&#8217;t answer what this question you have no idea what you are doing.</p>

<p>Why is this question so important?</p>

<p>Imagine building a house without knowing what a brick is. Or a nail. It would be very hard to get anywhere.</p>

<p>Answering this question provides the foundation on which you can build your engineering skill-set – or any other skill-set for that matter.</p>

<p>It ensures that you can keep your goal in mind and do not get distracted by desirable, but ancillary pursuits.</p>

<p>You shouldn&#8217;t be afraid because you don&#8217;t know the answer, and that shouldn&#8217;t stop you from working. But to have the good-sense to keep this question present will provide you with the necessary direction to achieve your goals.</p>

<p>Where should you start?</p>

<p>First, begin by paying attention. Listen to yourself. Feel your breath. Hold it. Control it. Breath out. Do that constantly.</p>

<p>This is only a start. The complex subject of &#8220;Self&#8221;, more specifically &#8220;Yourself&#8221; will require never-ending examination.</p>

<p>At some point in time, the bible and religion were great places to begin this discovery process but many of them have become politicized. Here is a list of 3 books that strongly base themselves on proof and science. Two of them are very theoretical with an exercise or two in between. The last one is a biography that will paint a picture of a living, breathing example of someone who embodied the qualities presented in the theories.</p>

